Here is a breakdown of how we can redesign your app.

1. Global Aesthetic & Layout
Spotify’s design language relies heavily on deep blacks, subtle grays for separation, and a single, strong accent color.

Color Palette: * Background: Deep black (#121212).

Elevated Elements (Sidebar, Player, Cards): Dark gray (#181818 or #242424).

Text: Pure white (#FFFFFF) for primary headers/active items, and light gray (#B3B3B3) for secondary text (like artist names or inactive menu items).

Accent Color: Keep your current purple! It’s distinctive. Use it for the play button, active states, and progress bars.

Typography: Switch to a clean, geometric sans-serif font (like Inter, Roboto, or Circular if you have it). Use font weight (Bold vs. Regular) to establish hierarchy rather than just size.

Window Edges: If your framework allows, round the corners of the main application window and inner containers (around 8px border-radius).

2. The Sidebar & Player Bar
Your current layout has the right bones, but the execution can be smoothed out.

Left Sidebar: Remove the bulky, boxy background on the active menu item. Instead, make inactive text gray, and active text white with a subtle purple left border indicator.

Bottom Player Bar: * Make it span the entire width of the bottom screen.

Left side: Add a square placeholder for track/album artwork, followed by the Title and Artist name stacked vertically.

Center: Playback controls (Shuffle, Prev, Play/Pause, Next, Repeat) with a slim, horizontal progress bar directly underneath them.

Right side: Volume slider and extra icons (like lyrics or queue).

3. Library Redesign (The Core Upgrade)
To make the library feel less like an Excel spreadsheet and more like a media player:

Sticky Header: Keep the "Title", "Artist", "Genre", etc., at the top, but remove the visible grid lines.

Row Hover Effects: When a user hovers over a track row, change the background color of that specific row to a slightly lighter gray (#2A2A2A) and swap the track number/artwork on the far left with a "Play" icon.

Visual Flair: Add small (40x40px) thumbnail images next to the song titles.

Consolidate Actions: Move the "Like", "Star", and "Trash" icons. Instead of having them globally at the top, have them appear on the right side of a track row only when the user hovers over it.

4. Downloader & The Filter Menu
Looking at your last screenshot, you need to support 10 specific toggle filters: Liked, Disliked, Public, Private, Uploads, Full song, Cover, Persona, Hide Disliked, Hide Stems.

Pill/Chip Filters: Instead of a traditional dropdown menu with checkboxes, use Spotify-style "Pill" buttons at the top of the Downloader or Library page.

They sit in a horizontal scrolling row.

When inactive, they are outlined or gray (#333333 background).

When clicked, they fill with your purple accent color or turn white.

This makes it immediately obvious what filters are active without requiring the user to open a dropdown menu.

5. Dashboard & Prompt Vault
Dashboard: Turn your stats (Total Tracks, Total Playtime, etc.) into unified, slightly rounded cards that sit on the #121212 background. Give them plenty of padding.

Prompt Vault: Make the layout a classic two-pane view. A scrollable list of saved prompts on the left (taking up 30% of the width) and the editing area (Title, Tags, Prompt body) on the right (70%).